description:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Second Step &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;is a leading mental health charity in the South West offering housing, support and hope to thousands of people with mental health and other problems.  Our goal is to inspire hope and deliver change for everybody and every community we work with.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Support Assistant&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hours              &lt;/strong&gt;37 hours&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Job Type        &lt;/strong&gt;Permanent&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Salary             &lt;/strong&gt;£16.777 - £18.333&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Location         &lt;/strong&gt;Bristol&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Our High Support Service provides tenancy related support to people with a range of complex needs including homelessness, drug and alcohol misuse, re-offending and mental health issues who require support to progress towards more independent living.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The service operates a rota system covering two projects, Wayland Court located in Fishponds and Homefield Court located in St George. You will be expected to provide support between 09:00 and 21:00 Monday through to Friday and 09:00 – 17:00 on Saturday.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You will be responsible for providing recovery focussed support to people, promoting independence and supporting vulnerable people in developing move on and recovery plans.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You will have a minimum of 1 years’ experience of working with people with complex needs in the social housing field. Experience and understanding of working with people with multiple needs, homelessness, mental health or drug/alcohol dependency is essential.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We work in a recovery focused psychologically informed way (PIE) and you will receive comprehensive training, regular supervision and be part of team reflective practice.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A full driving license and access to transport is desirable as the post involves travel between projects.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Closing date: &lt;/strong&gt;            20th November&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Interview dates(s)      27th November&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We’re committed to &lt;strong&gt;equal opportunities&lt;/strong&gt; and welcome applicants from all sections of the community including people who have &lt;strong&gt;personal experience of using mental health services&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
